{"title_page": "Lisa Baldez", "text_new": "{{short description|American political scientist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Lisa Baldez\n| image             =\n| image_upright     = \n| alt               = \n| caption           =\n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = \n| death_place       =\n| nationality       = [[United States|American]]\n| fields            = {{ubl|[[Political science]]|[[Latin American Studies]]}}\n| alma_mater        = {{ubl|[[Princeton University]]|[[ University of California, San Diego]]}}\n| workplaces        = {{ubl|[[Rochester Institute of Technology]]|[[University of Rochester]]|[[Washington University in Saint Louis]]|[[Harvard University]]|[[Dartmouth College]]}}\n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| doctoral_students = \n| known_for         = \n| awards            = {{ubl|[[Victoria Schuck|Victoria Schuck Award]], [[American Political Science Association|APSA]]}}\n}}\n'''Lisa Baldez''' is an [[United States|American]] [[political scientist]] and scholar of [[Latin American Studies]]. She is a Professor of Government and Latin American, Latino and Caribbean Studies at [[Dartmouth College]], where she was also Cheheyl Professor and Director of the Dartmouth Center for the Advancement of Learning at Dartmouth College from 2015 until 2018. She studies the relationship between [[Political system|political institutions]] and [[gender equality]], and has written about the [[United Nations]] [[Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women]], women's protests in [[Chile]], [[Women_in_government#Quotas|gender quota]] laws, and the [[Equal Rights Amendment]].\n\n==Education and early work==\nBaldez attended [[Princeton University]], where she earned a BA in Latin American Studies in 1986.<ref name=profile>{{cite web |url=https://faculty-directory.dartmouth.edu/lisa-baldez |title=Lisa Baldez |publisher=Dartmouth College |date=October 2018 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> She then completed an MA in political science at the [[University of California, San Diego]] in 1992, followed by a political science PhD there in 1997. Her dissertation received an Honorable Mention for the 1998 Best Dissertation Prize from the Women and Politics Section of the [[American Political Science Association]].<ref name=profile/>\n\nIn Spring of 1997, Baldez worked as an Adjunct Professor at The [[Rochester Institute of Technology]] and The [[University of Rochester]], and in 1997 she joined the political science faculty at [[Washington University in Saint Louis]].<ref name=profile/> From 1999 to 2002, Baldez was a Harbison Faculty Fellow at Washington University in Saint Louis.<ref name=profile/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://wp.las.iastate.edu/cattcenter/2009/10/13/catt-prize-winners/ |title=Carrie Chapman Catt Prize for Research on Women and Politics |publisher=Iowa State University |year=2013 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> In Spring 2003, she was a visiting professor at [[Harvard University]].<ref name=profile/> In 2003, she became a professor of Government and Latin American, Latino and Caribbean Studies at Dartmouth College.<ref name=profile/>\n\n==Career==\nIn 2002, Baldez published the book ''Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile'', in which she studies why women protest, and in what situations they make their gender identity salient as part of their protests.<ref name=noonan>{{cite journal |first=Rita K. |last=Noonan |title=Review of Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile |journal=Contemporary Sociology |volume=33 |issue=2 |pages=231\u2013232 |date=1 March 2004 |doi=10.1177/009430610403300260}}</ref> Baldez focuses on the struggle for [[women's suffrage]] in Chile,<ref>{{cite journal |first=Victor P. |last=Unda |title=Review of Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile |journal=Rocky Mountain Review of Language and Literature |volume=59 |issue=2 |pages=112\u2013114 |date=1 January 2005 |doi=}}</ref> and on two major episodes of protests by women in Chile during the 1970s and 1980s: the protests against [[Salvador Allende]] and against [[Augusto Pinochet]].<ref>{{cite journal |first=Patricia |last=Tomic |title=Review of Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile |journal=Canadian Journal of Latin American and Caribbean Studies / Revue canadienne des \u00e9tudes latino-am\u00e9ricaines et cara\u00efbes |volume=28 |issue=55/56 |pages=305\u2013307 |year=2003}}</ref> In both of these cases women's political mobilization was a major factor in undermining the legitimacy of a regime, even though these movements were in many ways ideologically opposite.<ref name=noonan/> Baldez theorizes that women form major social movements when partisan realignment gives them the opportunity to do so, and they are able to frame their exclusion from public life as a reason to protest apart from partisan differences,<ref>{{cite journal |first=Elisabeth Jay |last=Friedman |title=Review of Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile |journal=Political Science Quarterly |volume=118 |issue=3 |pages=531\u2013532 |date=1 October 2003}}</ref> and she tests this idea using [[archive|archival material]] and [[Interview (research)|research interviews]] with activists who were involved in the two movements.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Liesl |last=Haas |title=Review of Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile |journal=Perspectives on Politics |volume=1 |issue=4 |pages=799\u2013800 |date=1 December 2004}}</ref>\n\nBaldez published a second book, ''Defying Convention: US Resistance to the UN Treaty on Women's Rights'', in 2014. In ''Defying Convention'', Baldez studies why the United States was one of very few countries that had not ratified the United Nations Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women, which pledges to put an end to war and establishes gender equality.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Jocelyn |last=Olcott |title=Review of Defying Convention: US Resistance to the UN Treaty on Women's Rights |journal=Journal of American Studies |volume=51 |issue=4 |pages=1295\u20131297 |date=November 2017 |doi=10.1017/S0021875817001098}}</ref> Baldez examines this decision in the context of the historical development of a global norm of women's rights, and attributes American non-ratification partly to division among women's groups domestically on how best to achieve gender equality, and partly to United States obstructionism at the UN towards any initiatives by the [[Soviet Union]] and its allies.<ref name=davis>{{cite journal |first=Martha |last=Davis |title=Review of Defying Convention: US Resistance to the UN Treaty on Women's Rights |journal=Journal of Human Rights |volume=15 |issue=4 |pages=571\u2013573 |date=1 October 2016 |doi=10.1080/14754835.2016.1165089}}</ref> She also studies how the interpretation of the text of the treaty evolved in the years after its drafting, so that the effective meaning of ratifying the treaty might be understood to have changed over time, which complicates the study of why the United States did not ratify the text in different periods.<ref name=davis/> Baldez structures her discussion using historical [[process tracing]], and compares the possibility of America ratifying the Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women to its ratification of the [[International Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Racial Discrimination]] nearly 30 years after that convention's initial drafting.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Lana |last=Obradovic |title=Review of Defying Convention: US Resistance to the UN Treaty on Women's Rights |journal=International Feminist Journal of Politics |volume=17 |issue=3 |pages=515\u2013517 |date=3 July 2015 |doi=10.1080/14616742.2015.1055140}}</ref> ''Defying Convention'' won the 2015 Victoria Schuck Award from the American Political Science Association, which is given each year for \"the best book published on women and politics\" in the previous year.<ref name=schuck>{{cite web |url=https://www.apsanet.org/PROGRAMS/APSA-Awards/Victoria-Schuck-Award |title=Victoria Schuck Award |publisher=American Political Science Association |year=2019 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> It also won the 2015 Best Book Award from the Human Rights Section of the American Political Science Association.<ref name=besthr>{{cite web |url=https://www.apsanet.org/section-36-best-book-award |title=Best Book Award |publisher=American Political Science Association |year=2015 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to her articles in peer-reviewed academic journals and her chapters in edited books, Baldez was also an editor of the 2008 volume ''Political Women and American Democracy: Critical Perspectives on Women and Politics Research'', together with [[Christina Wolbrecht]] and Karen Beckwith.<ref name=profile/> From 2015 until 2018, Baldez was Cheheyl Professor and Director of the Dartmouth Center for the Advancement of Learning at Dartmouth College.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dcal.dartmouth.edu/about/history |title=Cheheyl Professor History |publisher=Dartmouth College |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nBaldez's work has been cited, or she has been quoted, in news outlets like ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/2016/5/18/11692402/parliaments-better-presidents-liberal |title=Justin Trudeau isn't magic, liberals. Parliaments make it easier to pass laws. |date=18 May 2016 |work=Vox |last=Matthews |first=Dylan |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> [[KQED-FM]], <ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kqed.org/news/11743996/the-equal-rights-amendment-what-you-need-to-know |title=The Equal Rights Amendment: What You Need to Know |date=30 April 2019 |work=KQED |last=Leitsinger |first=Miranda |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> and ''[[Bloomberg News]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2020-01-24/trump-impeachment-house-democrats-flatter-republican-senators-k5s5mzni |title=Democrats Try Flattery as Impeachment-Trial Tactic |date=24 January 2020 |work=Bloomberg |last=Bernstein |first=Jonathan |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n*''Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile'' (2002)\n*\"Elected Bodies: The Gender Quota Law for Legislative Candidates in Mexico\", ''Legislative Studies Quarterly'' (2011)\n*''Defying Convention: US Resistance to the UN Treaty on Women's Rights'' (2014)\n\n==Selected awards==\n*Victoria Schuck Award, American Political Science Association (2015)\n*Best Book Award, Human Rights Section of the American Political Science Association (2015)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baldez, Lisa}}\n[[Category:American women social scientists]]\n[[Category:American political scientists]]\n[[Category:Women political scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Princeton University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, San Diego alumni]]\n[[Category:Rochester Institute of Technology faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Rochester faculty]]\n[[Category:Washington University in St. Louis faculty]]\n[[Category:Harvard University faculty]]\n[[Category:Dartmouth College faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American political scientist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Lisa Baldez\n| image             =\n| image_upright     = \n| alt               = \n| caption           =\n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = \n| death_place       =\n| nationality       = [[United States|American]]\n| fields            = {{ubl|[[Political science]]|[[Latin American Studies]]}}\n| alma_mater        = {{ubl|[[Princeton University]]|[[University of San Diego]]}}\n| workplaces        = {{ubl|[[Rochester Institute of Technology]]|[[University of Rochester]]|[[Washington University in Saint Louis]]|[[Harvard University]]|[[Dartmouth College]]}}\n| doctoral_advisor  = \n| doctoral_students = \n| known_for         = \n| awards            = {{ubl|[[Victoria Schuck|Victoria Schuck Award]], [[American Political Science Association|APSA]]}}\n}}\n'''Lisa Baldez''' is an [[United States|American]] [[political scientist]] and scholar of [[Latin American Studies]]. She is a Professor of Government and Latin American, Latino and Caribbean Studies at [[Dartmouth College]], where she was also Cheheyl Professor and Director of the Dartmouth Center for the Advancement of Learning at Dartmouth College from 2015 until 2018. She studies the relationship between [[Political system|political institutions]] and [[gender equality]], and has written about the [[United Nations]] [[Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women]], women's protests in [[Chile]], [[Women_in_government#Quotas|gender quota]] laws, and the [[Equal Rights Amendment]].\n\n==Education and early work==\nBaldez attended [[Princeton University]], where she earned a BA in Latin American Studies in 1986.<ref name=profile>{{cite web |url=https://faculty-directory.dartmouth.edu/lisa-baldez |title=Lisa Baldez |publisher=Dartmouth College |date=October 2018 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> She then completed an MA in political science at the [[University of San Diego]] in 1992, followed by a political science PhD there in 1997. Her dissertation received an Honorable Mention for the 1998 Best Dissertation Prize from the Women and Politics Section of the [[American Political Science Association]].<ref name=profile/>\n\nIn Spring of 1997, Baldez worked as an Adjunct Professor at The [[Rochester Institute of Technology]] and The [[University of Rochester]], and in 1997 she joined the political science faculty at [[Washington University in Saint Louis]].<ref name=profile/> From 1999 to 2002, Baldez was a Harbison Faculty Fellow at Washington University in Saint Louis.<ref name=profile/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://wp.las.iastate.edu/cattcenter/2009/10/13/catt-prize-winners/ |title=Carrie Chapman Catt Prize for Research on Women and Politics |publisher=Iowa State University |year=2013 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> In Spring 2003, she was a visiting professor at [[Harvard University]].<ref name=profile/> In 2003, she became a professor of Government and Latin American, Latino and Caribbean Studies at Dartmouth College.<ref name=profile/>\n\n==Career==\nIn 2002, Baldez published the book ''Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile'', in which she studies why women protest, and in what situations they make their gender identity salient as part of their protests.<ref name=noonan>{{cite journal |first=Rita K. |last=Noonan |title=Review of Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile |journal=Contemporary Sociology |volume=33 |issue=2 |pages=231\u2013232 |date=1 March 2004 |doi=10.1177/009430610403300260}}</ref> Baldez focuses on the struggle for [[women's suffrage]] in Chile,<ref>{{cite journal |first=Victor P. |last=Unda |title=Review of Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile |journal=Rocky Mountain Review of Language and Literature |volume=59 |issue=2 |pages=112\u2013114 |date=1 January 2005 |doi=}}</ref> and on two major episodes of protests by women in Chile during the 1970s and 1980s: the protests against [[Salvador Allende]] and against [[Augusto Pinochet]].<ref>{{cite journal |first=Patricia |last=Tomic |title=Review of Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile |journal=Canadian Journal of Latin American and Caribbean Studies / Revue canadienne des \u00e9tudes latino-am\u00e9ricaines et cara\u00efbes |volume=28 |issue=55/56 |pages=305\u2013307 |year=2003}}</ref> In both of these cases women's political mobilization was a major factor in undermining the legitimacy of a regime, even though these movements were in many ways ideologically opposite.<ref name=noonan/> Baldez theorizes that women form major social movements when partisan realignment gives them the opportunity to do so, and they are able to frame their exclusion from public life as a reason to protest apart from partisan differences,<ref>{{cite journal |first=Elisabeth Jay |last=Friedman |title=Review of Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile |journal=Political Science Quarterly |volume=118 |issue=3 |pages=531\u2013532 |date=1 October 2003}}</ref> and she tests this idea using [[archive|archival material]] and [[Interview (research)|research interviews]] with activists who were involved in the two movements.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Liesl |last=Haas |title=Review of Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile |journal=Perspectives on Politics |volume=1 |issue=4 |pages=799\u2013800 |date=1 December 2004}}</ref>\n\nBaldez published a second book, ''Defying Convention: US Resistance to the UN Treaty on Women's Rights'', in 2014. In ''Defying Convention'', Baldez studies why the United States was one of very few countries that had not ratified the United Nations Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women, which pledges to put an end to war and establishes gender equality.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Jocelyn |last=Olcott |title=Review of Defying Convention: US Resistance to the UN Treaty on Women's Rights |journal=Journal of American Studies |volume=51 |issue=4 |pages=1295\u20131297 |date=November 2017 |doi=10.1017/S0021875817001098}}</ref> Baldez examines this decision in the context of the historical development of a global norm of women's rights, and attributes American non-ratification partly to division among women's groups domestically on how best to achieve gender equality, and partly to United States obstructionism at the UN towards any initiatives by the [[Soviet Union]] and its allies.<ref name=davis>{{cite journal |first=Martha |last=Davis |title=Review of Defying Convention: US Resistance to the UN Treaty on Women's Rights |journal=Journal of Human Rights |volume=15 |issue=4 |pages=571\u2013573 |date=1 October 2016 |doi=10.1080/14754835.2016.1165089}}</ref> She also studies how the interpretation of the text of the treaty evolved in the years after its drafting, so that the effective meaning of ratifying the treaty might be understood to have changed over time, which complicates the study of why the United States did not ratify the text in different periods.<ref name=davis/> Baldez structures her discussion using historical [[process tracing]], and compares the possibility of America ratifying the Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women to its ratification of the [[International Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Racial Discrimination]] nearly 30 years after that convention's initial drafting.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Lana |last=Obradovic |title=Review of Defying Convention: US Resistance to the UN Treaty on Women's Rights |journal=International Feminist Journal of Politics |volume=17 |issue=3 |pages=515\u2013517 |date=3 July 2015 |doi=10.1080/14616742.2015.1055140}}</ref> ''Defying Convention'' won the 2015 Victoria Schuck Award from the American Political Science Association, which is given each year for \"the best book published on women and politics\" in the previous year.<ref name=schuck>{{cite web |url=https://www.apsanet.org/PROGRAMS/APSA-Awards/Victoria-Schuck-Award |title=Victoria Schuck Award |publisher=American Political Science Association |year=2019 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> It also won the 2015 Best Book Award from the Human Rights Section of the American Political Science Association.<ref name=besthr>{{cite web |url=https://www.apsanet.org/section-36-best-book-award |title=Best Book Award |publisher=American Political Science Association |year=2015 |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to her articles in peer-reviewed academic journals and her chapters in edited books, Baldez was also an editor of the 2008 volume ''Political Women and American Democracy: Critical Perspectives on Women and Politics Research'', together with [[Christina Wolbrecht]] and Karen Beckwith.<ref name=profile/> From 2015 until 2018, Baldez was Cheheyl Professor and Director of the Dartmouth Center for the Advancement of Learning at Dartmouth College.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dcal.dartmouth.edu/about/history |title=Cheheyl Professor History |publisher=Dartmouth College |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nBaldez's work has been cited, or she has been quoted, in news outlets like ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'',<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.vox.com/2016/5/18/11692402/parliaments-better-presidents-liberal |title=Justin Trudeau isn't magic, liberals. Parliaments make it easier to pass laws. |date=18 May 2016 |work=Vox |last=Matthews |first=Dylan |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> [[KQED-FM]], <ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kqed.org/news/11743996/the-equal-rights-amendment-what-you-need-to-know |title=The Equal Rights Amendment: What You Need to Know |date=30 April 2019 |work=KQED |last=Leitsinger |first=Miranda |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref> and ''[[Bloomberg News]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2020-01-24/trump-impeachment-house-democrats-flatter-republican-senators-k5s5mzni |title=Democrats Try Flattery as Impeachment-Trial Tactic |date=24 January 2020 |work=Bloomberg |last=Bernstein |first=Jonathan |access-date=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n*''Why Women Protest: Women's Movements in Chile'' (2002)\n*\"Elected Bodies: The Gender Quota Law for Legislative Candidates in Mexico\", ''Legislative Studies Quarterly'' (2011)\n*''Defying Convention: US Resistance to the UN Treaty on Women's Rights'' (2014)\n\n==Selected awards==\n*Victoria Schuck Award, American Political Science Association (2015)\n*Best Book Award, Human Rights Section of the American Political Science Association (2015)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baldez, Lisa}}\n[[Category:American women social scientists]]\n[[Category:American political scientists]]\n[[Category:Women political scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Princeton University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of San Diego alumni]]\n[[Category:Rochester Institute of Technology faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Rochester faculty]]\n[[Category:Washington University in St. Louis faculty]]\n[[Category:Harvard University faculty]]\n[[Category:Dartmouth College faculty]]\n", "name_user": "Astrophobe", "label": "safe", "comment": "whoops, USD -> UCSD", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lisa_Baldez"}
